    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>TAX EVASION BILL FOR IRISH BANK</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Brian Lavery</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Lavery, Brian</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bank of Ireland pays 30.5 million Irish pounds ($37 million) in back taxes, interest and penalties on bogus nonresident accounts held from 1986 to 1999; bank had estimated its liability would be less than 1.5 million Irish pounds; other Irish banks could face smiliar charges as audits are completed (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Hit with a far higher bill than it had expected, the Bank of Ireland paid 30.5 million Irish pounds ($37 million) in back taxes, interest and penalties on bogus nonresident accounts held from 1986 to 1999. The bank, Ireland's second-largest financial institution, had estimated that its liability would be less than 1.5 million Irish pounds. Other Irish banks could face similar charges as audits are completed.</p>
        <p>Brian Lavery (NYT)</p>
      </block>
